## 0x06 staff.bountypay.h1ctf.com

The staff portal at a first look seems almost read-only, the only dynamic parts are:
- the `login` page;
- the `$_GET["template"]` parameter which allows using a specific website section;
- the `profile` tab where you can edit your name and your avatar;
- the `Report This Page` feature, which sends an URL to the admin fo review.

Doing some more recon I found something very interesting in the [website.js](https://staff.bountypay.h1ctf.com/js/website.js):
```js
$(".upgradeToAdmin").click(function() {
    let t = $('input[name="username"]').val();
    $.get("/admin/upgrade?username=" + t, function() {
        alert("User Upgraded to Admin")
    })
}), $(".tab").click(function() {
    return $(".tab").removeClass("active"), $(this).addClass("active"), $("div.content").addClass("hidden"), $("div.content-" + $(this).attr("data-target")).removeClass("hidden"), !1
}), $(".sendReport").click(function() {
    $.get("/admin/report?url=" + url, function() {
        alert("Report sent to admin team")
    }), $("#myModal").modal("hide")
}), document.location.hash.length > 0 && ("#tab1" === document.location.hash && $(".tab1").trigger("click"), "#tab2" === document.location.hash && $(".tab2").trigger("click"), "#tab3" === document.location.hash && $(".tab3").trigger("click"), "#tab4" === document.location.hash && $(".tab4").trigger("click"));
```

Basically, if we can force the admin into visiting a webpage containing an `<input name="username" value="sandra.allison">` and into clicking an HTML element with an `upgradeToAdmin` class our user will be upgraded to admin.

With these objectives in mind, I tried to find which of the dynamic parts I can abuse.

### login page
The login page reflects the content of the `$_GET["username"]` variable into the `<input name="username">` value attribute.

### $_GET["template"]
After fuzzing the `$_GET["template"]` parameter I discovered that it is parsed as an `array` too, so I can include more than one template on each page.
For example visiting the following URL results in a page containing the `home` and the `login` templates:
https://staff.bountypay.h1ctf.com/?template[]=home&template[]=login

{F860572}

### profile page
The profile page allows you to edit the profile picture which is set as an HTML class of a div while reading a ticket.

### Report this page
The report this page allows to send any relative https://staff.bountypay.h1ctf.com/ URLs, but for the ones in the `/admin/` section.

At this point I was still missing one point, because I can send to the admin a page containing:
- an `<input name="username" value="sandra.allison">` HTML element;
- an HTML element with a `upgradeToAdmin` class.
But the admin is not clicking that element.

Going back to the `website.js` code I noticed the following code:
```js
document.location.hash.length > 0 && ("#tab1" === document.location.hash && $(".tab1").trigger("click"), "#tab2" === document.location.hash && $(".tab2").trigger("click"), "#tab3" === document.location.hash && $(".tab3").trigger("click"), "#tab4" === document.location.hash && $(".tab4").trigger("click"));
```

If in the `URL` ends with `#tab1` a click is done to the element having the class `tab1`, so if I add that class to the same element which has the `upgradeToAdmin` one it will be clicked!

### Privilege Escalation

Wrapping everything up:
1. Login as `sandra.allison`
2. In the `Profile` tab click update, intercept the request and replace the `profile_avatar` parameter with `tab1 upgradeToAdmin`
3. Click on the `Report To Admin`, intercept the request, `base64_decode` the `url` parameter, replace it with `/?template[]=login&username=sandra.allison&template[]=ticket&ticket_id=3582#tab1` and finally `base64_encode` it
4. Visit https://staff.bountypay.h1ctf.com/?template=home and note the new `Admin` tab

{F860567}


